00:41.860 --> 00:50.020
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. British-born author James P. Hogan has gained
a reputation as one of the premier writers of hard science fiction working today.

00:50.020 --> 00:59.240
He's published seven novels so far including Inherit the Stars, The Gentle
Giants of Ganymede, Giant Star, Thrice Upon a Time, The Two Faces of Tomorrow,

00:59.240 --> 01:11.260
and his latest Voyage from Yesteryear. Hogan tells us how he became an author.
When I left school at uh when I was 16 and wanted to be a writer then. I guess

01:11.260 --> 01:22.320
it was you know something that I always enjoyed doing as a kid at school. You
know the essays and the story writing exercises you get. And uh when I left

01:22.320 --> 01:34.480
school I told the world I was going to be a writer, and it seemed a good idea
until somebody said well with all the accumulated wisdom and experience of 16

01:34.480 --> 01:43.840
years what are you going to write about that the world is breathlessly waiting
to hear? And uh I hadn't thought about that, and the answer was not a lot. So I

01:43.840 --> 01:55.900
went away into engineering and electronics and computers and things like that
for something like 20 years. And I suppose the the the interest in in writing

01:55.900 --> 02:05.440
probably never went away. For 20 years, Hogan worked as a systems designer for
computers and sold computers to scientists for use in their research. Associating

02:05.440 --> 02:12.820
with scientists as he did, Hogan was exposed to all sorts of current scientific
research, and he would make use of his scientific contacts when he began to write

02:12.820 --> 02:24.440
seriously. I made use of my customers pretty freely as consultants um which was
kind of handy, but I found that I had customers who were brain surgeons and other

02:24.440 --> 02:33.780
customers who were studying pieces of rock brought back from the Apollo missions,
and um other guys who were building in you know or investigating machine

02:33.780 --> 02:44.240
intelligence. Just about any of the topics or the the favorite themes of
science fiction that you could pick out of a hat. The chances were sort

02:44.240 --> 02:53.260
of not 10 to 1. I had a customer specializing in that field and I just had to, if
I needed some background information on a particular, topic, I could almost

02:53.260 --> 03:02.660
guarantee I had a phone number in my diary of a guy who could talk all day about
it and uh they love doing it as well. I used to call them and uh if they'd like

03:02.660 --> 03:11.480
to come and talk to you tomorrow uh well we're a little busy but what's it about?
Oh uh I need some help with the book I'm working on well why didn't you say so?

03:11.480 --> 03:26.420
What time do you want to show up? And they talk all day. And I think this is
one of the uh interesting sides of selling computers into this kind of area. You

03:26.420 --> 03:37.660
can imagine some of these specialists specialists they talk to bacteria all day
long or whatever and they end up shut in the back rooms of universities and

03:37.660 --> 03:48.700
maybe there are four people on the planet they can talk to who understand their
language and uh sometimes they find it hard to believe that somebody from the

03:48.700 --> 03:59.220
the world outside that has walked in off the street is sincerely interested to
sit down and talk to them and he's curious he wants to know what they're doing,

03:59.220 --> 04:10.400
he wants to have it explained. So writing about his experiences with scientists
Hogan found that he was a science fiction writer. I didn't particularly set out

04:10.400 --> 04:19.240
to be a science fiction writer. I suppose I became one by accident I just always
wanted to write and started writing stories about the little bit of life that

04:19.240 --> 04:28.880
I'd had some personal experience of and was told I was a science fiction writer
and I said how's that? They said well the publisher is publishing it under their

04:28.880 --> 04:38.040
science fiction imprint so we guess you have to be. So I said okay. And it kind of
started out like that. Hogan's books are scientifically accurate and highly

04:38.040 --> 04:44.700
realistic. He's been called the man who put science back into science fiction
next time we'll talk to James P. Hogan about some of his novels.

