17:39.940 --> 17:47.960
This is Daryl Lane, and David Carson. Time travel is one of the traditional
themes of science fiction. One of the best, certainly one of the most realistic

17:47.960 --> 17:56.460
time travel books, is James Hogan's Thrice Upon a Time, which came out in 1980.
But for some time, for a number of years, in fact, before I wrote Thrice Upon a

17:56.460 --> 18:08.280
Time, I'd been wanting to write a time travel book for a number of reasons.
Firstly, I wanted to attempt to face up to the paradoxes, the logical paradoxes,

18:08.380 --> 18:22.320
once and for all, and answer them without cop-outs, without convenient
coincidences, and without obliging characters who just happened to do the right

18:22.320 --> 18:25.440
thing to make everything come out the way the author said.

18:29.480 --> 18:40.620
And secondly, I wanted to get away from this kind of cliche of some kind of a
conjurer's box, described or disguised as whatever, that you jump into and you

18:40.620 --> 18:51.640
jump out of and you're in some other time. We've seen too many conjurer's boxes,
and it seemed to me unrealistic. If I ever build a box like that, and I thought

18:51.640 --> 19:00.300
it was going to take me to another time, I certainly wouldn't jump into it and
press the button. I would conduct a long series of tests and experiments first,

19:00.400 --> 19:09.680
and none of our heroes ever seem to do this. Hogan wanted to avoid some of the
clichÃ©s or formulas that characterized most time travel stories. I think in too

19:09.680 --> 19:20.220
many stories, time machines are used like starships. They're just a device, a
vehicle, to get some characters into an unusual environment, and then tell a

19:20.220 --> 19:29.380
pretty routine story that was stolen from Greek mythology or European medieval
history. And the technology doesn't come into the story at all. They could have

19:29.380 --> 19:41.820
gone there on a Greyhound bus. I didn't want to do that. And so the story was
about some physicists who had stumbled upon this phenomenon and had realized

19:41.820 --> 19:53.560
that if what they were seeing meant what they thought it meant, it meant that
they could actually inject information into the past and change the past, with

19:53.560 --> 19:54.820
all the questions that implies.

20:06.220 --> 20:14.180
The strange thing the physicists learn is that they can send messages into the
past, not far into the past, maybe just ten minutes. I didn't want it to be a

20:14.180 --> 20:24.580
million years or a billion years or some huge span of time where really nothing
that you did could make any difference. How about a lab bench experiment? Ten

20:24.580 --> 20:34.020
minutes. You can just send a little signal back to yourself ten minutes ago and
change what you've already done. This is interesting. You're hard up against the

20:34.020 --> 20:44.560
paradoxes now. You can't find a way around them or duck them. You've got to
answer the question, what happens? The logic of it, the whole situation becomes

20:44.560 --> 20:54.020
absolutely, it drives you to the point of insanity trying to figure it out. It
was the logic and the science implied by the time travel theme that fascinated

20:54.020 --> 21:01.660
Hogan. He wanted to approach the concept realistically. And it's so realistic
that you feel, after reading the book, you could go down to Radio Shack and buy

21:01.660 --> 21:09.620
the parts to make a time travel machine. Recently, a number of responsible
scientists have been speculating on the actual possibility of time travel. We

21:09.620 --> 21:18.440
asked Hogan if he thought it would ever be a reality and if his book was meant
to be prophetic. Well, I don't know whether it's prophetic or not. Well, as is

21:18.440 --> 21:29.000
elaborated in the book itself, if something like that ever became a fact, there
are some pretty interesting problems that are going to have to be solved. And

21:29.000 --> 21:39.200
our ideas of logic and cause and effect are going to have to undergo some pretty
interesting revisions. So, I'm certainly not setting myself up as a prophet and

21:39.200 --> 21:49.060
saying, yes, it'll happen. Maybe, I don't know. I think history has shown that
impossible or it'll never happen are very dangerous phrases to use in any

21:49.060 --> 21:52.200
context. More with James P. Hogan next time.

