23:27.200 --> 23:35.520
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Of all science fiction writers working
today, no one surpasses James P. Hogan in scientific accuracy and realism.

23:35.520 --> 23:42.940
Hogan's publisher, Ballantine Books, has advertised them as the man who put
science back in science fiction. And after reading books like Thrice Upon a Time

23:42.940 --> 23:49.940
and The Two Faces of Tomorrow, you realize how much he deserves that
description. Hogan is also concerned with realism, with the kind of everyday

23:49.940 --> 23:57.520
detail that makes a story, even though it's set in the future, a totally
believable one. He explains why realistic detail is important. I think these

23:57.520 --> 24:14.240
kinds of details do matter because if we're putting a story into a futuristic
setting, I think the little details of background, such as if the guy needs to

24:14.240 --> 24:24.360
make a phone tour, how does he go about it if he needs to rent a cab, these
matter because if the story is being told in the future, the whole of the

24:24.360 --> 24:37.140
background has to be consistently futuristic. I've come across a number of
instances which, in my opinion, are a little flawed because it's spelt with an

24:37.140 --> 24:52.380
AW. A writer may have seized on a particular thought, maybe a new scientific
idea or a machine or whatever, develops that very well, but kind of gets hung up

24:52.380 --> 24:57.460
on it and in the background, everything else that's going on hasn't changed
since 1980.

25:01.180 --> 25:08.780
And trying to, I think, just stop typing for the five minutes it takes just to
think about a situation. The guy's going to make a phone call, just like stop

25:08.780 --> 25:22.740
and think how he might make that and think about it for five minutes and then
maybe show it in a way different to what would have been the impulsive thing to

25:22.740 --> 25:24.240
do in the first couple of seconds.

25:32.840 --> 25:40.220
Hogan says that his readers appreciate his attention to realistic detail and
accuracy. In fact, he thinks he attracts some readers who don't normally read

25:40.220 --> 25:53.100
science fiction because of it. From the people who write to me and the people
that I meet, one of the gratifying things I observe in the readership that I

25:53.100 --> 26:04.640
have is that it is not confined to what might be termed the hardcore science
fiction reader who buys anything new that appears on the science fiction section

26:04.640 --> 26:16.380
of the bookstores. But a lot of, I suppose, people who might be termed younger
professional people in their late 20s, 30s, 40s, in all manner of professions,

26:16.400 --> 26:28.280
not necessarily to do with the sciences, teachers, lawyers, doctors, so forth,
who typically would say, gee, I used to read science fiction when I was at

26:28.280 --> 26:38.260
college or when I was at university, but I kind of grew out of it. And I can't
relate to way out galaxies like years away anymore or aliens running around with

26:38.260 --> 26:50.280
ray guns. Today I have a family, a career, a mortgage, my feet are solidly on
the surface of this planet. But they seem to like stories that don't kind of try

26:50.280 --> 26:58.000
and take them to the other side of the universe a million years from now, but
maybe just stretch the future 20 or 30 years. And they find names in the book

26:58.000 --> 27:09.360
like IBM and Avis and Boeing. In familiar places. And it kind of grabs them. I
say, well, you know, this I can relate to. It's the world that I live in just

27:09.360 --> 27:17.080
stretched a little bit. The connection is not broken. The economics and the
politics have evolved from what I read in the papers. I can still see the

27:17.080 --> 27:26.140
connections. And it could be the world my kids grow up in. And I like it.
Hogan's latest novel, Voyage from Yesteryear, is further in the future than his

27:26.140 --> 27:33.480
other books. And the field of action is much broader. But it's typically Hogan
in his credibility. If you haven't been exposed to James P. Hogan's brand of

27:33.480 --> 27:35.280
science fiction, you're missing something.

